{
  "abstract" : [
    {
      "text" : "Setting up a project that can seamlessly use C APIs from the Pico SDK.",
      "type" : "text"
    }
  ],
  "hierarchy" : {
    "paths" : [
      [
        "doc:\/\/EmbeddedSwift\/documentation\/EmbeddedSwift"
      ]
    ]
  },
  "identifier" : {
    "interfaceLanguage" : "swift",
    "url" : "doc:\/\/EmbeddedSwift\/documentation\/EmbeddedSwift\/IntegrateWithPico"
  },
  "kind" : "article",
  "metadata" : {
    "role" : "article",
    "roleHeading" : "Article",
    "title" : "Raspberry Pi Pico SDK"
  },
  "primaryContentSections" : [
    {
      "content" : [
        {
          "anchor" : "overview",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Overview",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "content" : [
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "Embedded Swift is experimental. Public releases of Swift do not support Embedded Swift, yet. See ",
                  "type" : "text"
                },
                {
                  "identifier" : "doc:\/\/EmbeddedSwift\/documentation\/EmbeddedSwift\/InstallEmbeddedSwift",
                  "isActive" : true,
                  "type" : "reference"
                },
                {
                  "text" : " for details.",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "paragraph"
            }
          ],
          "name" : "Note",
          "style" : "note",
          "type" : "aside"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Development for ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/www.raspberrypi.com\/products\/raspberry-pi-pico\/",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " normally uses the ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/github.com\/raspberrypi\/pico-sdk",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " and the vendor provides several ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "https:\/\/github.com\/raspberrypi\/pico-examples",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : ". The SDK and sample project setup is described in:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "identifier" : "https:\/\/www.raspberrypi.com\/documentation\/microcontrollers\/c_sdk.html#sdk-setup",
                      "isActive" : true,
                      "type" : "reference"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "identifier" : "https:\/\/datasheets.raspberrypi.com\/pico\/getting-started-with-pico.pdf",
                      "isActive" : true,
                      "type" : "reference"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Before trying to use Swift with the Pico SDK, make sure your environment works and can build the provided C\/C++ sample projects.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "CMake-setup-with-a-bridging-header",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "CMake setup with a bridging header",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The Pico SDK is using CMake as its build system, and so the simplest way to integrate with it is to also use CMake to build a Swift firmware application on top of the SDK and the libraries from it. The following describes an example set up of that on a “blinky” example (code that just blinks the built-in LED).",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Let’s create a directory with a Swift source file, a bridging header, and a CMake definition file:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            ".\/SwiftPicoBlinky\/Main.swift",
            ".\/SwiftPicoBlinky\/BridgingHeader.h",
            ".\/SwiftPicoBlinky\/CMakeLists.txt"
          ],
          "syntax" : null,
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "In ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "Main.swift",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ", let’s add basic logic to initialize the GPIO port for the Pico’s built-in LED, and then turn it on and off in a loop:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "@main",
            "struct Main {",
            "  static func main() {",
            "    let led = UInt32(PICO_DEFAULT_LED_PIN)",
            "    gpio_init(led)",
            "    gpio_set_dir(led, \/*out*\/true)",
            "    while true {",
            "      gpio_put(led, true)",
            "      sleep_ms(250)",
            "      gpio_put(led, false)",
            "      sleep_ms(250)",
            "    }",
            "  }",
            "}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "swift",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Notice that we’re using functions and variables defined in C in the Pico SDK. For that to be possible, the Swift compiler needs to have access to the C header files that define these functions and variables. The cleanest option would be to define a modulemap, but for simplicity let’s just use a bridging header to make declarations visible in Swift without a module. ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "BridgingHeader.h",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " should contain:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "#pragma once",
            "",
            "#include \"pico\/stdlib.h\""
          ],
          "syntax" : "c",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Finally, we need to define the application’s build rules in CMake that will be using CMake logic from the Pico SDK. The following content of ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "CMakeLists.txt",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " leverages CMake 3.29’s native Swift language support:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.29)",
            "include($ENV{PICO_SDK_PATH}\/external\/pico_sdk_import.cmake)",
            "",
            "project(swift-blinky)",
            "pico_sdk_init()",
            "",
            "# Enable Swift language support",
            "enable_language(Swift)",
            "",
            "# Set Swift compilation mode to whole module optimization",
            "set(CMAKE_Swift_COMPILATION_MODE wholemodule)",
            "",
            "add_executable(swift-blinky Main.swift)",
            "set_target_properties(swift-blinky PROPERTIES ",
            "  LINKER_LANGUAGE CXX)",
            "",
            "target_compile_options(swift-blinky PUBLIC \"$<$<COMPILE_LANGUAGE:Swift>:SHELL:",
            "  -enable-experimental-feature Embedded",
            "  -target armv6m-none-none-eabi -Xcc -mfloat-abi=soft -Xcc -fshort-enums",
            "  -Xfrontend -function-sections",
            "  -import-bridging-header ${CMAKE_CURRENT_LIST_DIR}\/BridgingHeader.h",
            ">\")",
            "",
            "target_link_libraries(swift-blinky",
            "  pico_stdlib hardware_uart hardware_gpio",
            ")",
            "",
            "pico_add_extra_outputs(swift-blinky)"
          ],
          "syntax" : "cmake",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Configure-and-build",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Configure and build",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "With these three files, we can now configure and build a Swift firmware for the Pico:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "$ export PICO_BOARD=pico",
            "$ export PICO_SDK_PATH=<path_to_pico_sdk>",
            "$ export PICO_TOOLCHAIN_PATH=<path_to_arm_toolchain>",
            "$ ls -al",
            "-rw-r--r--   1 kuba  staff    39B Feb  2 22:08 BridgingHeader.h",
            "-rw-r--r--   1 kuba  staff   650B Feb  2 22:08 CMakeLists.txt",
            "-rw-r--r--   1 kuba  staff   262B Feb  2 22:08 Main.swift",
            "$ mkdir build",
            "$ cd build",
            "$ cmake -S ..\/ -B . -G Ninja",
            "$ ninja -v"
          ],
          "syntax" : "bash",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "This should produce several build artifacts in the ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "build\/",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " subdirectory, include ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "swift-blinky.uf2",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ", which can be directly uploaded to the Pico by copying it into the fake Mass Storage Volume that the device presents when plugged over USB in BOOTSEL mode.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
  ],
